37:17.769 --> 37:35.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: President Obama
awarded the Medal of Honor today
to retired Army Captain Florent

37:35.120 --> 37:40.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Groberg for risking his life to
stop a suicide bomber in
Afghanistan.

37:40.592 --> 37:46.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The 32-year-old French-born
soldier, who often goes by Flo,
is just the 10th living service

37:46.998 --> 37:53.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
member to receive the nation's
highest military honor for
actions in Afghanistan or Iraq.

37:53.371 --> 37:56.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States: And so it was on
an August day three years

37:56.708 --> 38:02.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ago that Flo found himself
leading a group of American and
Afghan soldiers as they escorted

38:02.046 --> 38:06.351 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
their commanders to a
meeting with local Afghans.

38:06.351 --> 38:11.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was a journey that the team
had done many times before -- a
short walk on foot, including

38:11.556 --> 38:15.293 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
passage over a narrow bridge.

38:15.293 --> 38:20.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Flo noticed something to his
left -- a man, dressed in dark
clothing, walking backwards,

38:20.798 --> 38:26.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just some 10 feet away. The man
spun around and turned toward
them, and that's when Flo

38:26.804 --> 38:31.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sprinted toward him. He pushed
him away from the formation, and
as he did, he noticed an

38:31.843 --> 38:36.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
object under the man's
clothing -- a bomb.

38:36.581 --> 38:39.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And at that moment, Flo did
something extraordinary -- he
grabbed the bomber by his vest
and kept

38:39.517 --> 38:43.655 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
pushing him away.

38:43.655 --> 38:48.526 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of Flo's comrades, Sergeant
Andrew Mahoney, had joined in,
too, and together they shoved

38:48.526 --> 38:52.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the bomber again and again. And
they pushed him so hard he fell
to the ground onto his

38:52.530 --> 38:56.201 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
chest. And then the
bomb detonated.

38:56.201 --> 39:02.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ball bearings, debris, dust
exploded everywhere. Flo was
thrown some 15 or 20 feet and
was

39:02.740 --> 39:06.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
knocked unconscious. And moments
later, he woke up in the middle
of the road in shock.

39:06.644 --> 39:10.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His eardrum was blown out. His
leg was broken and bleeding
badly.

39:10.748 --> 39:17.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That blast by the bridge claimed
four American heroes -- four
heroes Flo wants us to remember

39:17.188 --> 39:19.324 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today.

39:19.324 --> 39:26.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of his mentors, a 24-year
Army vet, Command Sergeant Major
Kevin Griffin.

39:26.998 --> 39:31.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A West Pointer who loved hockey
and became a role model to
cadets and troops because

39:31.402 --> 39:36.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he always cared more about other
people than himself, Major Tom
Kennedy.

39:36.674 --> 39:43.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A popular Air Force leader known
for smiling with his whole face,
Major David Gray.

39:43.681 --> 39:49.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, finally, a USAID foreign
service officer, a man who moved
to the United States from

39:49.420 --> 39:57.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Egypt and reveled in everything
American, Ragaei Abdelfattah.

39:57.929 --> 40:04.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We honor Flo because his actions
prevented an even greater
catastrophe. You see, by pushing

40:04.702 --> 40:09.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the bomber away from the
formation, the explosion
occurred farther from our
forces, and on the

40:09.907 --> 40:15.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ground instead of in the open
air. And while Flo didn't know
it at the time, that explosion

40:15.113 --> 40:21.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also caused a second, unseen
bomb to detonate before it was
in place.

40:21.052 --> 40:26.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The truth is, Flo says that day
was the worst day of his life.
And that is the stark reality

40:26.791 --> 40:33.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
behind these Medal of Honor
ceremonies, because on his very
worst day, he managed to summon

40:33.698 --> 40:42.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his very best. That's the nature
of courage, not being unafraid,
but confronting fear and

40:42.940 --> 40:49.080 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
danger and performing
in a selfless fashion.

40:49.080 --> 40:53.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He showed his guts. He showed
his training, how he would put
it all on the line for his

40:53.985 --> 40:57.155 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
teammates. That's an American
we can all be grateful for.

40:57.155 --> 41:02.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's why we honor Captain
Florent Groberg today.

41:02.760 --> 41:08.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: The president of the United
States of America, authorized by
act of Congress, March

41:08.900 --> 41:12.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
3, 1863, has awarded in the name
of Congress the Medal of Honor
to Captain Florent A. Groberg,

41:12.704 --> 41:14.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
United States Army.

41:14.172 --> 41:16.674 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

41:16.674 --> 41:25.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAPT. FLORENT GROBERG, U.S.
Army: This medal is the greatest
honor you could ever receive.

41:25.083 --> 41:30.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I am blessed and just
grateful to have been given the
opportunity to serve my country.

41:30.822 --> 41:36.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this medal belongs to the
true heroes, Command Sergeant
Griffin, Major Gray, Major

41:36.928 --> 41:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kennedy, and Ragaei Abdelfattah,
who made the ultimate sacrifice
and didn't come home.

41:42.033 --> 41:47.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It also belongs to their
families, the true heroes who
live with that day every day
missing

41:47.138 --> 41:49.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
one of the key members
of their families.

41:49.907 --> 41:59.250 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I'm honored. I'm overwhelmed,
but I hope to become the right
carrier for them and better

41:59.250 --> 42:12.530 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
