JEFFREY BROWN: You
love everything?

46:30.488 --> 46:35.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIETTE BINOCHE: I don't put
things aside. No, I think it's
another -- it's like painting.

46:35.893 --> 46:40.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, you love different
styles, because it shows
someone's need to express
something.

46:40.931 --> 46:48.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I feel the need, that's
beyond style. I don't care where
it comes from, which country,

46:48.406 --> 46:51.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
what period, because
it has truth.

46:51.876 --> 46:56.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The reference to
painting is a personal one.
Binoche did her own paintings

46:56.147 --> 47:01.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for a film in which she played
an artist, and has even had
exhibitions of her work.

47:01.986 --> 47:08.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Curious or restless, she's
thrown herself into all kinds of
things, including performing

47:08.893 --> 47:12.263 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on stage in contemporary dance.

47:12.263 --> 47:19.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIETTE BINOCHE: I like to
confront myself with new
perspectives and possibilities,
because

47:19.170 --> 47:26.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think, we're alive, so let's
do it now. And we have so many
possibilities. So, I don't

47:26.911 --> 47:30.347 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like to stay in one
comfortable place.

47:30.347 --> 47:35.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There is much
discussion, again, about --
especially about women actresses

47:35.519 --> 47:42.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
aging, not getting as many good
roles, what happens to them. Do
you even think about that?

47:42.927 --> 47:50.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIETTE BINOCHE: I think if you
keep yourself creative -- I
mean, I have aged, you know?

47:50.167 --> 47:57.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have had experience. And so
it's not as if I'm not facing
it.

47:57.308 --> 48:03.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's not a fear, because
time is a tool to grow. If you
don't have that tool, how

48:03.647 --> 48:11.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can you grow? How can you
transform? So you have to
believe that time is your best
friend.

48:11.088 --> 48:15.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Imagine if you have to die when
you're young. You feel like,
wow. What I have learned with

48:15.059 --> 48:18.062 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
time is amazing.

48:18.062 --> 48:23.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right,
Juliette Binoche, thank you so
much.

48:23.400 --> 48:30.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JULIETTE BINOCHE: Thank you.

48:30.608 --> 48:38.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Finally tonight,
another installment in our
series of "NewsHour" essays.

48:38.115 --> 48:42.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Essays are part of a long
tradition on the "NewsHour," and
in the coming weeks and months,

48:42.386 --> 48:47.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we hope to bring you a range of
voices as varied as the ideas
they will share with you.

48:47.424 --> 48:52.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, author Ylonda Gault
shares her view on a
particularly challenging
personality:

48:52.096 --> 48:53.898 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the bragging parent.

48:53.898 --> 48:59.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YLONDA GAULT, Author: It will
start innocently, a chance
run-in.

48:59.036 --> 49:03.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I will see a fellow mom at the
grocery store or the park, maybe
a coffee shop. I will say,

49:03.841 --> 49:08.212 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hey, girl. We will hug. At least
I will, because I'm a hugger.

49:08.212 --> 49:13.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I will compliment her outfit.
She may notice my new
highlights. We will trade
innocent

49:13.384 --> 49:20.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gossip. I will ask about her
work, then the family, to which
she will respond with a sigh,

49:20.891 --> 49:26.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as though fatigued, because, for
moms, every season touts tired
as the new black.

49:26.931 --> 49:35.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thus begins the humble brag,
feigning exasperation. Said mom
will half-giggle and wax
self-mocking.

49:35.005 --> 49:42.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, Sophie scored 2,200 on her
MDNM SATs, despite this slacker
mom, who forgot to get

49:42.746 --> 49:46.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
new calculator batteries. And
Zach's fourth grade teacher
recommended him for advanced

49:46.717 --> 49:49.320 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
calculus.

49:49.320 --> 49:53.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Meanwhile, his dad and I don't
still get new math, old math, or
even everyday math. These

49:53.824 --> 49:57.361 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kids, I tell you.

49:57.361 --> 50:05.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A wan smile will wash over my
face. It's the expression I
usually reserve for my
8-year-old

50:05.069 --> 50:11.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when he's regaling with my
intricate details of obscure
superheroes and their powers.

50:11.041 --> 50:16.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When she laughs and throws her
head back, I do the same thing
on the outside. Inside,

50:16.280 --> 50:23.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I wince, and whisper to myself,
bless her heart, as momma would
say.

50:23.687 --> 50:29.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For black people, those sweet
little words are a nice way of
saying, how pitiful.

50:29.493 --> 50:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a gracious phrase, and I
mean it in the best possible
way, because a part of me truly

50:35.633 --> 50:41.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
aches to see a grown woman,
smart and accomplished in her
own right, boasting about her
children

50:41.505 --> 50:45.109 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as though they were prized
heifers at the county fair.

50:45.109 --> 50:51.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's odd to me, because,
growing up, momma always played
down what my siblings and I

50:51.415 --> 50:58.455 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
did. It may be a black thing,
but I think it's also an
old-school thing. No one wanted

50:58.455 --> 51:02.626 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
their kids to get too
big-headed, I suppose.

51:02.626 --> 51:08.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Importantly, parenting wasn't an
extreme sport back in the day.
And, remember, there was

51:08.832 --> 51:14.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no Facebook. Social media posts
are the lifeblood of the humble
braggart.

51:14.672 --> 51:20.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I get it. They feel less secure
in their own worth, so tethered
are the kiddos to their

51:20.110 --> 51:25.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
own self-image, the offsprings'
accomplishments become their
own.

51:25.749 --> 51:32.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Intellectually, I know most
studies will show that mothers
and fathers hell-bent on this

51:32.189 --> 51:37.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
image of perfection desperately
need the world to take note of
their kids' awesomeness. It's

51:37.528 --> 51:45.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a way of saying, see, my kids
are great. Therefore, I am
great. Look at me. See? I'm a
great parent.

51:45.402 --> 51:48.706 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Really, I am.

51:48.706 --> 51:56.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do they believe it? Sadly, I
don't think so. It's not that
these parents don't have good

51:56.580 --> 52:03.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kids. I mean, all kids are good,
right, just like all babies are
-- ahem -- cute.

52:03.120 --> 52:10.361 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
See, all moms lie. As the humble
braggart prattles on, I pretend
to listen. And when

52:10.361 --> 52:19.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
she's done, I put on my best
girlfriend face and try to sound
super astonished. I say,

52:19.903 --> 52:27.511 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wow. Go, you.

52:27.511 --> 52:35.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: On the "NewsHour"
online: Earlier this week, we
introduced you to a man who's

52:35.319 --> 52:40.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
